        1,
        "**Lines, Angles, and Triangles** form the foundation of SAT geometry. Mastering the relationships between angles is the single fastest way to gain points on this domain.\n\n"
        "**Angle types:** An **acute angle** measures less than 90 degrees. A **right angle** measures exactly 90 degrees (marked with a small square in diagrams). An **obtuse angle** measures between 90 and 180 degrees. A **straight angle** measures exactly 180 degrees and forms a straight line. Two angles are **complementary** when their measures sum to 90 degrees; they are **supplementary** when their measures sum to 180 degrees.\n\n"
        "**Angle relationships at intersecting lines:** When two lines intersect, they create two pairs of **vertical angles** -- the angles directly across from each other. Vertical angles are always equal. For example, if one angle is 47 degrees, the vertical angle is also 47 degrees. The two adjacent angles at the same intersection are supplementary, summing to 180 degrees. All four angles around a single point always sum to 360 degrees.\n\n"
        "**Parallel lines cut by a transversal:** When a transversal crosses two parallel lines, it creates eight angles. Three key relationships appear on every SAT:\n"
        "- **Corresponding angles** occupy the same position at each intersection (e.g., both in the upper-left corner). They are equal.\n"
        "- **Alternate interior angles** lie between the parallel lines on opposite sides of the transversal. They are equal.\n"
        "- **Co-interior (same-side interior) angles** lie between the parallel lines on the same side of the transversal. They are supplementary -- they add to 180 degrees.\n\n"
        "**Triangle angle-sum theorem:** The three interior angles of any triangle always sum to exactly 180 degrees. This is the most-used geometry fact on the SAT. If two angles are known, the third is simply 180 minus their sum.\n\n"
        "**Exterior angle theorem:** An exterior angle of a triangle equals the sum of the two non-adjacent (remote) interior angles. If a triangle has angles 40, 65, and 75 degrees, the exterior angle at the 75-degree vertex equals 40 + 65 = 105 degrees. This shortcut is faster than computing the interior angle first and then subtracting from 180.\n\n"
        "**Similar triangles:** Two triangles are **similar** when their corresponding angles are equal and their corresponding sides are proportional. The three similarity shortcuts are:\n"
        "- **AA (Angle-Angle):** If two pairs of corresponding angles are equal, the triangles are similar.\n"
        "- **SAS (Side-Angle-Side):** Two pairs of sides proportional with the included angles equal.\n"
        "- **SSS (Side-Side-Side):** All three pairs of sides proportional.\n"
        "If the similarity ratio is 1:k, side lengths scale by k, areas scale by k squared, and perimeters scale by k.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 1:** Two parallel lines are cut by a transversal. One angle measures (3x + 10) degrees and its alternate interior angle measures (5x - 30) degrees. Find x.\n"
        "- Alternate interior angles are equal: 3x + 10 = 5x - 30.\n"
        "- Subtract 3x: 10 = 2x - 30. Add 30: 40 = 2x, so x = 20.\n"
        "- Check: 3(20) + 10 = 70 and 5(20) - 30 = 70. Confirmed.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 2:** In triangle ABC, angle A = 52 degrees and angle B = 74 degrees. An exterior angle is drawn at vertex C. Find the exterior angle.\n"
        "- Exterior angle = sum of remote interior angles = 52 + 74 = 126 degrees.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 3:** Triangle PQR is similar to triangle STU with ratio 3:5. Side PQ = 12. Find side ST.\n"
