        2,
        "**Circles** appear on nearly every SAT math section. The good news is that every circle question flows from a small set of formulas and theorems -- learn them cold and circle problems become reliably fast points.\n\n"
        "**Core definitions:** The **radius** (r) is the distance from the center to any point on the circle. The **diameter** (d) is twice the radius: d = 2r. A **chord** is any line segment connecting two points on the circle. The **diameter** is the longest possible chord.\n\n"
        "**Fundamental formulas:**\n"
        "- **Circumference:** C = 2*pi*r = pi*d (the total distance around the circle)\n"
        "- **Area:** A = pi*r^2 (always use the radius, never the diameter)\n\n"
        "**Arcs and sectors:** An **arc** is a portion of a circle's circumference. A **sector** is the pie-slice region bounded by two radii and an arc. Both are calculated as a fraction of the full circle based on the **central angle** (the angle at the center):\n"
        "- **Arc length** = (central angle / 360) * 2*pi*r\n"
        "- **Sector area** = (central angle / 360) * pi*r^2\n"
        "Think of these as: (fraction of the full circle) * (full circumference or area).\n\n"
        "**Central angle and arc measure:** A central angle and its intercepted arc have the same degree measure. A central angle of 90 degrees intercepts a 90-degree arc, which is one-quarter of the circle.\n\n"
        "**Inscribed angle theorem:** An **inscribed angle** has its vertex on the circle and its two sides as chords. An inscribed angle equals exactly half the central angle that intercepts the same arc. If the central angle is 100 degrees, the inscribed angle is 50 degrees. A special case: any inscribed angle that intercepts a semicircle (180-degree arc) is always 90 degrees -- this is **Thales' theorem**.\n\n"
        "**Tangent lines:** A line is **tangent** to a circle if it touches the circle at exactly one point. The key property: a tangent line is always perpendicular to the radius drawn to the point of tangency. This creates a right angle, making the Pythagorean theorem usable whenever a tangent appears.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 1 -- Arc length:** A circle has radius 9. A sector has a central angle of 80 degrees. Find the arc length.\n"
        "- Arc length = (80/360) * 2*pi*9 = (2/9) * 18*pi = 4*pi inches.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 2 -- Sector area:** A circle has radius 12 cm. The central angle is 150 degrees. Find the sector area.\n"
        "- Sector area = (150/360) * pi*12^2 = (5/12) * 144*pi = 60*pi sq cm.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 3 -- Missing central angle:** A sector has area 20*pi in a circle with radius 10. Find the central angle.\n"
        "- 20*pi = (theta/360) * pi*100. Divide both sides by pi: 20 = (theta/360)*100.\n"
        "- theta/360 = 20/100 = 1/5. So theta = 360/5 = 72 degrees.\n\n"
        "**Common traps:**\n"
        "- Using the **diameter instead of the radius** in A = pi*r^2. Always halve the diameter before squaring.\n"
        "- Confusing the **inscribed angle** with the **central angle**: the inscribed angle is half the central angle, not equal to it.\n"
        "- Forgetting to take the square root when asked for the radius after being given the area.\n\n"
        "**Tip:** On any arc or sector problem, write the fraction (central angle / 360) first and simplify it before multiplying. This prevents arithmetic errors and keeps numbers manageable."
