        3,
        "**Area and Volume** problems test your ability to select the right formula, substitute correctly, and handle composite shapes and scaling. The SAT formula sheet provides most formulas -- but knowing them cold is still faster.\n\n"
        "**Area formulas (2D):**\n"
        "- **Rectangle:** A = length * width\n"
        "- **Triangle:** A = (1/2) * base * height (height is always perpendicular to the base, not the slant side)\n"
        "- **Parallelogram:** A = base * height (again, perpendicular height)\n"
        "- **Trapezoid:** A = (1/2) * (base1 + base2) * height (average the two parallel bases, then multiply by height)\n"
        "- **Circle:** A = pi*r^2\n\n"
        "**Volume formulas (3D):**\n"
        "- **Rectangular prism (box):** V = length * width * height\n"
        "- **Cylinder:** V = pi*r^2*h\n"
        "- **Cone:** V = (1/3)*pi*r^2*h (exactly one-third of the cylinder with the same base and height)\n"
        "- **Sphere:** V = (4/3)*pi*r^3\n"
        "- **Pyramid:** V = (1/3) * base area * height\n\n"
        "**Surface area:** Surface area measures the total outer skin of a 3D solid.\n"
        "- **Rectangular prism:** SA = 2(lw + lh + wh) -- sum of areas of all 6 faces\n"
        "- **Cylinder:** SA = 2*pi*r^2 + 2*pi*r*h (two circular ends plus the lateral rectangle unrolled)\n"
        "- **Lateral area** refers only to the curved or side surfaces, excluding the bases.\n\n"
        "**Net-based thinking:** When visualizing surface area, imagine cutting the solid along edges and unfolding it flat. The cylinder's lateral surface unfolds into a rectangle with width 2*pi*r (the circumference) and height h.\n\n"
        "**Scaling -- the most tested concept in this area:**\n"
        "- If all linear dimensions are multiplied by a factor k, **area scales by k^2** and **volume scales by k^3**.\n"
        "- Example: doubling every dimension of a box (k = 2) multiplies the volume by 2^3 = 8.\n"
        "- This applies to similar solids: if radius doubles, cylinder volume becomes 4 times larger (k^2 affects r^2 inside pi*r^2*h, and k also scales h, giving k^3 overall).\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 1 -- Composite volume:** A cylinder has radius 3 ft and height 10 ft. A cone sits on top with the same base radius and height 4 ft. Find the combined volume.\n"
