        4,
        "**The Coordinate Plane** connects algebra and geometry. SAT questions in this area test distance, midpoints, slope, and circle equations -- all of which flow from a few key formulas.\n\n"
        "[[figure:coordinate_quadrants|The four quadrants and the signs of x and y in each]]\n\n"
        "**The four quadrants:** The x-axis and y-axis divide the plane into four quadrants. In Quadrant I, both x and y are positive. In Quadrant II, x is negative and y is positive. In Quadrant III, both are negative. In Quadrant IV, x is positive and y is negative. Knowing these sign patterns helps you check that answers are in a sensible location.\n\n"
        "**Distance formula:** The distance between (x1, y1) and (x2, y2) is:\n"
        "- d = sqrt((x2 - x1)^2 + (y2 - y1)^2)\n"
        "This is just the Pythagorean theorem in disguise: the horizontal difference is one leg, the vertical difference is the other leg, and d is the hypotenuse. On a grid, count the horizontal and vertical gaps first and apply a^2 + b^2 = c^2 -- it is faster than plugging four coordinates into the formula.\n\n"
        "**Midpoint formula:** The midpoint M of a segment from (x1, y1) to (x2, y2) is:\n"
        "- M = ((x1 + x2) / 2, (y1 + y2) / 2)\n"
        "Average the x-coordinates and average the y-coordinates separately.\n\n"
        "**Slope from two points:** The slope m of the line through (x1, y1) and (x2, y2) is:\n"
        "- m = (y2 - y1) / (x2 - x1) = rise / run\n"
        "- A positive slope rises left to right; negative slope falls left to right.\n"
        "- A horizontal line has slope 0. A vertical line has undefined slope.\n"
        "- **Parallel lines** share the same slope. **Perpendicular lines** have slopes that are negative reciprocals: m1 * m2 = -1.\n\n"
        "**Equation of a circle:** A circle with center (h, k) and radius r in the coordinate plane satisfies:\n"
        "- (x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2\n"
        "To read the center, note that the signs inside the parentheses are opposite the center coordinates: (x + 3)^2 means h = -3.\n\n"
        "**Completing the square:** When the circle equation is in expanded form (x^2 + y^2 + bx + cy + d = 0), rewrite it in standard form by completing the square for both x and y. Step-by-step: move the constant to the right, group x and y terms, add (b/2)^2 and (c/2)^2 to both sides, then factor.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 1 -- Distance:** Find the distance between (1, 2) and (7, 10).\n"
