        5,
        "**Right Triangles and the Pythagorean Theorem** appear in some form on virtually every SAT math section -- and the tools here extend far beyond basic triangles into 3D geometry, distance problems, and coordinate geometry.\n\n"
        "[[figure:pythagorean_triangle|Right triangle with legs a, b and hypotenuse c labeled]]\n\n"
        "**The Pythagorean theorem:** In any right triangle with legs a and b and hypotenuse c (the side opposite the right angle):\n"
        "- a^2 + b^2 = c^2\n"
        "Use it to find any missing side when the other two are known. If a = 6 and b = 8, then c^2 = 36 + 64 = 100, so c = 10.\n\n"
        "**Pythagorean triples:** These are sets of three positive integers that satisfy a^2 + b^2 = c^2. Memorizing them lets you skip all arithmetic:\n"
