        "- In a 30-60-90 triangle, assigning the longer leg to the 30-degree angle. The longer leg is always opposite the larger angle (60 degrees).\n"
        "- In a 45-45-90 triangle, thinking the hypotenuse equals x instead of x*sqrt(2).\n"
        "- Applying the Pythagorean theorem with the hypotenuse as a leg -- always confirm which side is opposite the right angle.\n\n"
        "**Tip:** Before computing, check if the two given sides form part of a known triple. If you see legs 5 and 12, write hypotenuse = 13 immediately. This habit saves a significant amount of time across the full test."
