        6,
        "**Trigonometric Ratios** let you find missing sides and angles in right triangles using three core ratios. The SAT tests these ratios directly, through the complementary identity, and by converting between degrees and radians.\n\n"
        "**SOH-CAH-TOA:** For an acute angle theta in a right triangle:\n"
        "- **sin(theta) = Opposite / Hypotenuse**\n"
        "- **cos(theta) = Adjacent / Hypotenuse**\n"
        "- **tan(theta) = Opposite / Adjacent**\n"
        "The mnemonic SOH-CAH-TOA encodes all three ratios. Always label sides relative to the angle in question: the **opposite** side is across from the angle; the **adjacent** side touches the angle but is not the hypotenuse.\n\n"
        "**Exact values table -- memorize these:**\n"
        "- sin(0) = 0, cos(0) = 1, tan(0) = 0\n"
        "- sin(30) = 1/2, cos(30) = sqrt(3)/2, tan(30) = sqrt(3)/3\n"
        "- sin(45) = sqrt(2)/2, cos(45) = sqrt(2)/2, tan(45) = 1\n"
        "- sin(60) = sqrt(3)/2, cos(60) = 1/2, tan(60) = sqrt(3)\n"
        "- sin(90) = 1, cos(90) = 0, tan(90) = undefined\n\n"
        "**Complementary angle relationship:** Because the two acute angles in a right triangle sum to 90 degrees, their sine and cosine are swapped:\n"
        "- sin(x) = cos(90 - x) and cos(x) = sin(90 - x)\n"
        "This appears on the SAT in the form: if sin(x) = cos(32), then x + 32 = 90, so x = 58. No calculator needed -- just recognize the identity.\n\n"
        "**Finding missing sides:** Set up the appropriate trig ratio, then solve by cross-multiplication.\n"
        "Example: A ladder 12 ft long leans against a wall at 60 degrees from the ground. How high does it reach?\n"
        "- sin(60) = height / 12. Height = 12 * sin(60) = 12 * (sqrt(3)/2) = 6*sqrt(3) ft.\n\n"
        "**Finding missing angles:** Use inverse trig functions.\n"
        "- arcsin, arccos, arctan (written sin^-1, cos^-1, tan^-1 on calculators)\n"
        "- If tan(theta) = 4/3, then theta = arctan(4/3). Use the calculator on non-standard angles.\n\n"
        "**Radians vs. degrees:** A full circle equals 360 degrees or 2*pi radians. The conversion formulas are:\n"
        "- Degrees to radians: multiply by pi/180\n"
        "- Radians to degrees: multiply by 180/pi\n"
        "- Key conversions: 30 = pi/6, 45 = pi/4, 60 = pi/3, 90 = pi/2, 180 = pi, 270 = 3*pi/2, 360 = 2*pi\n\n"
        "**Pythagorean identity:** sin^2(theta) + cos^2(theta) = 1. The SAT occasionally asks you to simplify expressions using this identity.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 1 -- Finding sin and cos:** In right triangle ABC, angle C = 90, AB = 13, BC = 5. Find sin(A) and cos(A).\n"
        "- AC = sqrt(13^2 - 5^2) = sqrt(144) = 12.\n"
        "- sin(A) = opposite/hypotenuse = BC/AB = 5/13.\n"
        "- cos(A) = adjacent/hypotenuse = AC/AB = 12/13.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 2 -- Complementary identity:** If cos(x) = sin(47), find x.\n"
        "- cos(x) = sin(47) = cos(90 - 47) = cos(43). So x = 43 degrees.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 3 -- Radian conversion:** Convert 270 degrees to radians.\n"
        "- 270 * (pi/180) = 270/180 * pi = 3/2 * pi = 3*pi/2 radians.\n\n"
        "**Common traps:**\n"
        "- Swapping **opposite** and **adjacent**. Relabel the triangle for each new angle before writing the ratio.\n"
        "- Using degree mode on the calculator when the problem is in radians, or vice versa.\n"
        "- Forgetting that tan(90) is undefined (the adjacent side length is zero).\n\n"
        "**Tip:** If you cannot recall an exact trig value during the test, quickly sketch the relevant special triangle (30-60-90 or 45-45-90) using the ratios from the SAT formula sheet and read off the ratio directly. This takes about 10 seconds and is more reliable than guessing from memory."
