    (
        7,
        "**SAT Geometry and Trigonometry Strategy** is about working smarter, not just harder. Knowing the content is necessary but not sufficient -- you also need a systematic approach for translating word problems into correct diagrams and solutions under timed pressure.\n\n"
        "**Using the SAT formula sheet:** The Digital SAT provides a reference sheet at the start of the math section. It includes:\n"
        "- Area formulas: triangle, circle\n"
        "- Volume and surface area: cylinder, cone, sphere, pyramid, rectangular prism\n"
        "- Special right triangles: 30-60-90 and 45-45-90 ratios\n"
        "- Circle: total degrees (360), semicircle (180)\n"
        "**Not on the sheet:** distance formula, midpoint formula, slope, trig ratios, arc length, sector area, the Pythagorean theorem. Know these from memory. Use the sheet freely -- there is no penalty for checking it, and doing so takes only a few seconds.\n\n"
        "**Strategy 1 -- Draw and label your own diagram:** When a question describes a geometric situation without a figure, sketch it immediately. Mark every given length and angle. Label the unknown with x and circle what the question actually asks for. Students who draw first consistently outperform students who try to hold the picture in their heads.\n\n"
        "**Strategy 2 -- Work backward from answer choices:** On multiple-choice geometry problems, plug answer choices back into the question. Start with a middle value when answers are ordered numerically (eliminates half the options on each try). This is especially effective for angle problems and side-length problems where setting up an equation takes longer than testing a value.\n\n"
        "**Strategy 3 -- Estimate with scale when diagrams are drawn to scale:** Many SAT figures are drawn to scale (the problem will say so, or will not include the 'not drawn to scale' note). Use the diagram to eliminate extreme answer choices. If the unknown angle looks close to 60 degrees, eliminate answers like 20 and 150 before solving.\n\n"
        "**When to use the Pythagorean theorem vs. trigonometry:**\n"
        "- Use the **Pythagorean theorem** when you know two sides and need the third -- no angle required.\n"
        "- Use **trigonometry** (SOH-CAH-TOA) when you know one side and one acute angle and need another side, OR when you know two sides and need an angle.\n"
        "- Use **special triangle ratios** (30-60-90, 45-45-90) as a shortcut when angles are 30, 45, or 60 -- faster than trig.\n\n"
        "**Common SAT geometry trap types:**\n"
        "- **Radius vs. diameter:** Halve the diameter before using any area or arc formula.\n"
        "- **Forgetting units:** If lengths are in centimeters, area is in cm^2 and volume is in cm^3. Mixing units (cm and m in the same problem) is a trap.\n"
        "- **Degrees vs. radians:** Identify which the question uses before computing. An answer in radians and an answer in degrees for the same angle look completely different numerically.\n"
        "- **Answering the wrong quantity:** The question might ask for 2x + 3 after you find x = 5. Always re-read the final question before bubbling in your answer.\n"
        "- **'Not drawn to scale':** If a diagram carries this warning, trust the numbers -- not the picture. Diagrams can be misleading by design.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 1 -- Multi-step composite area:** A large square has side 10. A circle is inscribed inside it (touching all four sides). Find the shaded area between the square and circle.\n"
        "- Square area = 100. Circle radius = 5. Circle area = 25*pi.\n"
        "- Shaded area = 100 - 25*pi.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 2 -- Working backward:** A question asks for the angle in a triangle and the answer choices are 30, 45, 60, and 75 degrees. You know two angles are equal and sum to 90 degrees. Testing 45: two equal angles of 45 sum to 90, leaving the third angle as 90. That satisfies the constraint. Answer: 45 degrees.\n\n"
        "**Worked Example 3 -- Pythagorean vs. trig:** A right triangle has hypotenuse 10 and one acute angle of 30 degrees. Find both legs.\n"
        "- Use special triangle: shorter leg = 10/2 = 5 (opposite 30). Longer leg = 5*sqrt(3) (opposite 60). Faster than using sin and cos individually.\n\n"
        "**Common traps (summary):**\n"
        "- Solving for x when the question asks for x + 5.\n"
        "- Using slant height where perpendicular height is required.\n"
        "- Mixing up inscribed angle and central angle (inscribed = half of central).\n\n"
        "**Tip:** Before submitting any geometry answer, do a 5-second sanity check: Is the answer a reasonable size given the figure? Does it have the right units? Did you answer what was asked? This habit catches a significant percentage of careless errors without requiring re-solving the problem."
    ),
